messages.message:
Patch Set 14:

> Andreas Dilger		12:29 PM

> Patch Set 14:

> John, using strlcpy() is problematic between userspace and kernel space.

> It may be that it was fixed, but there were problems in the past due to the glibc maintainer refusing to add strlcpy() to the library. We might have fixed it by just deleting the use of strlcpy() entirely.

The kernel defines it and we're using it in several places. I'd like to see no new uses of strnxxx() in the lustre source. (not to speak of strcpy() and strcat()). There are several places where they're used incorrectly. And too often it takes too much time to determine if a given use is valid and ends up NUL terminated. Here are some examples:

 if (lo->ldo_pool)
         strncpy(v3->lmm_pool_name, lo->ldo_pool,
                                LOV_MAXPOOLNAME);

--

 strncpy(new_pool->pool_name, poolname, LOV_MAXPOOLNAME);
 new_pool->pool_name[LOV_MAXPOOLNAME] = '\0';

--

 strncpy(oi->oi_name, name, OSD_OI_NAME_SIZE - 1);

I always just ask people to use snprintf().
